[SIZE=4][B]Core Concepts[/B][/SIZE]

Lib3DObjects is build to be extensible and easy to use. It provides several base classes that can be extended to create custom 3D objects with specific behaviors.
There are a lot of premade Objects that can be used directly or extended.

There are two base types that all 3D objects derive from:

[LIST]
[*][B]BaseObject[/B]: The base class for all 3D objects. It provides basic functionality such as position, rotation, scale, callbacks, and visibility.
[*][B]BaseObjectGroup[/B]: A container for multiple BaseObjects. It allows for collective transformations and management of its child objects.
[/LIST]

With these base classes, you can create various types of 3D objects, such as:

[LIST]
[*][B]Point[/B]: A simple point in 3D space.
[*][B]Arrow[/B]: An arrow that can be used to indicate direction in 3D space.
[*][B]Text[/B]: 3D text that can be placed in the game world.
[*][B]Texture[/B]: A 2D texture that can be placed in 3D space.
[*][B]Marker[/B]: A marker that can be placed in 3D space, with options for different textures, animations, text and custom behaviours.
[*][B]Line[/B]: A line segment between two points in 3D space.
[/LIST]

Callbacks can be registered to objects to update their properties dynamically, e.g. to make them follow a player or rotate over time. This also allows for creating reactive objects that change based on player actions or game events.
There are several premade animation that can be used to animate objects, e.g. spinning, bouncing, pulsing, etc.

Renderers are used to define how objects are drawn in the game world. Different renderers can be used for different types of objects, allowing for customization of appearance and behavior. The currently available renderers are:

[LIST]
[*][B]WorldSpaceRenderer[/B]: Renders objects in the 3D world over everything else. It allows you to see the objects through obstacles. This is the default renderer for most objects. With this you can render EVERY Control in 3D Space.
[*][B]RenderSpaceRenderer[/B]: Renders objects in render space, allowing them to use a depth buffer and be occluded by world geometry. This is useful for creating objects that interact with the environment more realistically. This renderer ONLY supports TextureControls. That's just a limitation of the ESO API.
[/LIST]

